I believe in the principles and beliefs that Democrats do. I'm very liberal, leaning towards a leftist, so being a Democrat just works for me. I have to say, I am VERY disappointed in the Democrats and their lack of action in preventing Trump from rising to power.

question: when_decided_pid
text: I've identified as a moderate for as long as I can remember.
full_text: I've identified as a moderate for as long as I can remember.   In recent years, both the Republican and Democratic parties have grown increasingly divisive and extreme, prioritizing partisan loyalty over collaboration and common ground. Rather than working together to solve pressing national issues, each side often resorts to vilifying the other, creating a toxic political climate that fuels polarization and alienates moderate voices. This growing extremism has eroded public trust in government and made compromise seem like a weakness instead of a strength. As a result, meaningful policy progress is frequently stalled, and the needs of everyday Americans are lost in the noise of ideological battles.

full_text: I left New York state to get a better paying job and Inrease my standard of living by moving to North Carolina but I returned to New York because I had a young son who needed me   I was a staunch Democrat for most of my adult life and a union member. I was kind of center in most of my beliefs but the democrats seemed to more be in line with my values. Then they started to come after my guns and I began leaning towards the right and then they started wanting more rights for pregnant women and had no regard for the voiceless children and I leaned farther right. Then as a state employee whose union supported our democrat governor I watched as he adopted the same position regarding our union as the republican candidate and I began to vote republican. Then the affirmative action came and I as a management employee of the state was forced to hire not the best candidates for the job but minority candidates and I was required to stay within a strict budget while dropping my current suppliers of many different items and replacing them with other suppliers who sold the same products but at budget shattering inflated prices from minority owned businesses and I realized that the democrats were not about equality but about a whole different agenda and it kept getting worse to the point that I could no longer consider myself a centered democrat or even a right leaning one because the center line for me was so far to the right that I had no choice especially because it's only gotten worse with gays having special rights that I as a heterosexual don't have or minorities getting special treatment even though they are hardly a minority anymore and I couldn't understand why we didn't have equal rights anymore but specialized rights. The gun laws they keep proposing make it harder for me to get a weapon or ammunition to defend myself while they cry to defund the police so I can be defenseless and the bar keeps getting lowered in areas such as faith and abortion, the government in the hands of the left was leaning towards totalitarianism and I stopped recognizing my country anymore as they weakened our military and opened our borders and then told me there's more than two genders and our fucking sex was assigned at birth and we could change it at will contrary to the science they propose to support. That's why I am a registered republican and I consider myself a conservative because the few values I share with the liberals are not even considered left leaning any longer. I could write a book about it but my overpriced expired bacon that I got from the dumpster of my local supermarket where the blue haired gender fluid chick with a dick who was getting paid $20 an hour to take out the garbage chased me away because it was better that I should starve to protect its rights than for me to eat there fucking garbage.

text: At 25 years old, I voted for George HW Bush because I wanted smaller gov't even when I was a federal employee. But as I got older and started to learn of the policies and goals of the different parties I started to vote for Democrats.
full_text: At 25 years old, I voted for George HW Bush because I wanted smaller gov't even when I was a federal employee. But as I got older and started to learn of the policies and goals of the different parties I started to vote for Democrats.   The Democratic party's policies and goals align with my values. I'm pro choice, equal rights for all, pro democracy. I believe everyone should be able to live their lives the way they want as long as it doesn't infringe on my rights. Today the Republican politicians are just too cruel. I want a voting system where I can vote for two people and have a runoff with the top two vote getters. This way a third or fourth party will have a chance in the elections.   Born and raised in Hawaii, served in military 4 years, moved back in 1975.

In high school, they basically taught that the Democratic party was more modern and more for letting people do whatever they want with their lives with minimal gvnt intervention- which in theory sounds great. Who wouldn't want the freedom to make their own choices? When I was in college, I remember one of my professors asking if abortion was right or wrong. I answered that it's fine because the baby in the womb doesnt have consciousness and they dont know whats going on, so to set the pregnant woman up for a good life, it was acceptable. This was what we were programmed in school to believe - you can't have a baby and be successful. I was so ignorant. In my 20s, I learned about abortions and what they actually were, and that they stole the life of a person with unique code of DNA. Babies do have consciousness pre-birth and that is shown by their reactivity in the belly and their playfullness pre-birth. Looking back, it seemed like being a young democrat was the cool thing to do and showed to be more open minded. This was back when gays marrying was a huge thing. I thought that the gvnt should mind their own business about who wants to marry who so that was the leading decision for me. I thought the people should have freedom of choice with their own bodies, which I was not educated on. I still believe the gays should be able to marry, but the way things have been progressing with society regarding this trans stuff, whoever said it was a slippery slope was totally correct. I feel as if the democratic party preys on young people and convinces them to side with them with a common-sense kind of approach, although it is incredibly misleading. After reflecting on what i think is important to me and what aligns with my values, the Republican party definitely resonated more with me.

question: why_are_pid
text: I'm a humanist. I believe in basic human rights, and those include life, liberty, in the pursuit of happiness. If life is one of those rights – that means health. that means every American deserves to be able to eat, to have secure shelter, and be able to take care of their body on the most basic levels. Liberty requires that you feel able to do things. This is not permission. This is ability. Liberty doesn't mean you get to do whatever you want, but it does mean you can discuss and have the opportunity to explore options and situations. If you transgress others' liberty, that is an infringement of their rights. With liberty you are not punished for thoughts or expressions, nor are you forced to accept others thoughts or expressions. Once your life and health are guaranteed, and your ability for free thought are guaranteed, you get the ability to pursue happiness. This is an individual thing. I believe that while the Democratic Party is not great at this, they understand that collective good – results in individual freedom. The whole point of government should be collective good, not selective control.

question: when_think_pid
text: I was in college when I first began identifying with the Democratic party. This was during the second George W. Bush administration, and then just as Obama was elected for the first time.
full_text: I was in college when I first began identifying with the Democratic party. This was during the second George W. Bush administration, and then just as Obama was elected for the first time.   I wanted to move back to where I grew up   I identify more with progressives than I do with the Democratic party, proper. But I consider myself a Democrat because I believe in the principle that government should steward and benefit citizens through public works, research and funding, and social support programs. I also believe that the neoliberalization of government since the 1980s has catastrophically widened the wealth gap and failed to deliver benefits to all but the most wealthy Americans. Over the past decade, I have seen a terrifying rise of racist, bigoted, and patently misinformed views associated with the GOP and Donald Trump as its figurehead. I am exhausted by the discrimination this party aims at American citizens, those who wish to become citizens, and those who enter our country in need of asylum. I am exhausted by the vitriol towards BIPOC folks and the LGBTQ community. I am terrified that childbearing people will not get the healthcare they need because of abortion bans. I am terrified that Donald Trump is single-handedly destroying our economy and our respected position in world politics. And I am ashamed that our country has elected Donald Trump as president for a second term.

full_text: Better housing options available, better commute to work and school.   I want to live in a society where hungry people get fed and unhoused people get shelter. I want education to be close to free at all levels and for capitalism to have firm guardrails that keep corporations from exploiting workers. I want bodily autonomy for all women and I believe LGBTQIA+ Americans deserve to live and thrive, with dignity and protections under law. I think that abortion is healthcare and that healthcare is a human right. I believe there is systemic and structural racism in our country and it continues to cause great harm to our citizens today. How to identify and dismantle racist ideology should be taught in schools, discussed in public forums, and supported by legislation. I value art and science equally, and want them funded and supported by my tax dollars. I want robust public health programs, including screenings, vaccinations, and sex education. I want our top-earning 5% of citizens to pay higher tax rates than they currently pay. I think every worker in America should be paid a living wage for full time work. I want common sense gun laws that allow us to limit the type, size, and magazine capacity of what is sold, and impose lifetime bans for people convicted of domestic violence. I would like to see America adopt ranked choice voting in elections, especially at the federal level. I want to continue to work with our international allies to support democracy and combat poverty. I believe people seeking asylum should be treated humanely at the border and families should stay together whenever possible. The values and goals that I wish to see reflected in my community are most frequently supported by the Democratic party.

They keep us distracted by sowing seeds of discord over social issues, all while working together to make the rich even more wealthy by passing laws that favor those who line their pockets and fund their campaigns. The system is a duopoly and benefits only the wealthy capitalists, leaving the rest of the country to fight over the scraps. They view us as peasants. They work to undermine our education system in order to keep us stupid, without critical thinking skills. This country is a worldwide joke, and I'm ashamed of what we've become.

question: why_are_pid
text: I was a republican for a long time. It was the 2016 election of Donald Trump which changed me. I see myself as a moderate - I believe in equality, I believe in freedom, I believe in the US as the main power in the world. All of that has gone away from the GOP. The GOP is now a strange religious death cult. I became a D, and now a strong D because in the end, while I don't agree with everything on that side, I agree with the general intellectual approach and that the Ds believe in things like the rule of law, equality, and global standing. Also, after seeing the GOP tank the economy over and over, my analytical brain said "stop voting red if you don't want to go broke." So, here I am, an accidental democrat.

question: why_are_pid
text: Democrats have been the closest to my priorities since I started voting. I voted Republican a few times, but once I learned more about things, I saw how wrong I was. Democrats legislate more for interests of Americans like me. Before my disability, I worked as a Pipefitter, even though a few on the local and state level here are allies, they won't be satisfied until unions are a thing of the past. I believe socially as Democrats, not far left progressives. I believe in a hand up to those in need followed by a path forward, job training, counseling, etc. I'm big on climate change. I'm all for equal rights for all, regardless of religion, creed, sexual orientation, etc. I stand firm on separation of Church and State. As a practicing Catholic, I have no right setting an agenda we run the country. I believe in strong public schools and public universities with fully funded budgets. I don't want to hear there's never a reason to terminate a pregnancy because a politician identifies as pro life to win elections. I want sex education at an appropriate age with enough information to cut down on STI's and unwanted pregnancies. As a survivor, I wish mine in freshman year was more than a couple semesters in place of gym class. Maybe I would have spoken up for help sooner. I want to see abortion only in cases of rape, incest, and health of the mother. I want no more free passes for any religious congregation talking politics while making endorsements from the pulpit. I don't want immunity for anyone, including cops. Lastly, after 2015, I believe the biggest threat to America is our bought and paid for judiciary. full_text: Democrats have been the closest to my priorities since I started voting. I voted Republican a few times, but once I learned more about things, I saw how wrong I was. Democrats legislate more for interests of Americans like me. Before my disability, I worked as a Pipefitter, even though a few on the local and state level here are allies, they won't be satisfied until unions are a thing of the past. I believe socially as Democrats, not far left progressives. I believe in a hand up to those in need followed by a path forward, job training, counseling, etc. I'm big on climate change. I'm all for equal rights for all, regardless of religion, creed, sexual orientation, etc. I stand firm on separation of Church and State. As a practicing Catholic, I have no right setting an agenda we run the country. I believe in strong public schools and public universities with fully funded budgets. I don't want to hear there's never a reason to terminate a pregnancy because a politician identifies as pro life to win elections. I want sex education at an appropriate age with enough information to cut down on STI's and unwanted pregnancies. As a survivor, I wish mine in freshman year was more than a couple semesters in place of gym class. Maybe I would have spoken up for help sooner. I want to see abortion only in cases of rape, incest, and health of the mother. I want no more free passes for any religious congregation talking politics while making endorsements from the pulpit. I don't want immunity for anyone, including cops. Lastly, after 2015, I believe the biggest threat to America is our bought and paid for judiciary. The obstruction McConnell used blocking that many nominees across all levels to satisfy Leonard Leo and the dark money folks has set us back. We now have hand picked allies in districts where the cases shouldn't be heard setting the stage for everything to go to SCOTUS. There they're set to get rid of experts, agencies, and rights thar will harm America for generations.

question: why_think_pid
text: Because people who subscribe to one side or the other seem to get lost and believe one side is “all wrong” or “all right”. “Republican”, “democrat”, “liberal”, “far-right”, etc., I see as labels that are divisive. You express certain views on a matter stating that you’re part of either of those groups, your viewpoint and voice are stifled if it’s not agreeable to what’s commonly or politically correct. You have freedom of speech until you say something someone doesn’t like. It’s an incredible challenge for us as people to have conversations or productive, healthy arguments, without involving emotions, misunderstanding one another, making assumptions and so on. My thoughts may be all over the place, but the point is, I identify as nonpartisan because left wing, right wing, we’re all part of the same bird (the country), flapping in a direction and if we don’t remember the purpose it’ll crash.

You have freedom of speech until you say something someone doesn’t like. The differences between the parties no longer boil down to anything truly meaningful; the Democrats seem intent on destroying the whole of America and turning it into yet another Socialist/Communist shithole dictatorship. And the Republicans seem intent on feigning obliviousness in order to protect "the system;" a system purposefully designed to keep the general populace infuriated and fighting among ourselves while they grow fat off our tax dollars. Both parties essentially profit off our destruction and suffering. Look at every federal and state politician. Every one of them left office with a much higher net worth than they went in, and by a margin exponentially larger than their salary. All except one. Donald Trump is the only "politician" in over a century who actually LOST a significant portion of his net worth by being in office (about 1/3). That is a fine illustration of why the people voted for him: because unlike EVERY other person to ever hold office he is actually serving US. Not himself, not "the system," not some trillionaire family pulling strings in a few dozen other countries. America first.

full_text: 2016   I grew up as an evangelical Christian who listened to Rush Limbaugh and later Fox News. When I came out as a gay man in 2012, I began to experience what it was like to be an “other.” I began to see the world differently from a political perspective. I felt so torn that I didn’t vote for president in 2012. I had always voted Republican. I knew Republicans weren’t my friends anymore but couldn’t vote for a Democrat. I then started seeing Nancy Pelosi very differently. And then Trump happened. I was appalled that people were supporting him, and I turned to the Democrats during the 2016 election. After Jan. 6 and everything that has happened, I don’t see myself ever supporting a Republican again.   Family

question: why_are_pid
text: I consider myself a leftist, not a Democrat. My closeness to the Democratic Party is mostly a matter of political necessity—there is no viable mainstream alternative that aligns even remotely with my values. The Republican Party has shifted so far to the right, embracing authoritarian, exclusionary, and often anti-democratic ideologies, that I could never support it in its current form. I used to identify as a Marxist, but over time I’ve come to see that Marx's framework doesn’t fully capture the realities of our current technofeudal era. So while I still care deeply about justice, equity, and dismantling systems of oppression, I now simply call myself a leftist.

question: when_think_pid
text: I have always thought of myself as a Democrat and have been a registered member of the Democrat Party since I turned 18 and became eligible.
full_text: I have always thought of myself as a Democrat and have been a registered member of the Democrat Party since I turned 18 and became eligible.   Family moved for new jobs   I have always been politically and socially progressive. I have always considered myself a Democrat because I had long thought that being a Democrat was synonymous with being a leftist. Slowly over the course of the last several years, as I became more educated and more politically aware and as I saw Democratic politicians move further to the right, I have become very disillusioned with the party. I disagree, to varrying extents, with much of the party's platform and am even more disappointed with the Democrats' perpetual inertia and outright refusal to deliver on even their most basic of campaign promises. Even though I hate the Democrat Party -- especially at the federal level -- I nonetheless have been a registered Democrat since I turned 18 and have always voted exclusively for Democrat candidates, and I do not expect that to change, purely because the Republicans are so much worse than the Democrats and all Independent/3rd party candidates are totally non-viable.

Family moved for new jobs   I have always been politically and socially progressive. I have always considered myself a Democrat because I had long thought that being a Democrat was synonymous with being a leftist. Slowly over the course of the last several years, as I became more educated and more politically aware and as I saw Democratic politicians move further to the right, I have become very disillusioned with the party. I disagree, to varrying extents, with much of the party's platform and am even more disappointed with the Democrats' perpetual inertia and outright refusal to deliver on even their most basic of campaign promises. Even though I hate the Democrat Party -- especially at the federal level -- I nonetheless have been a registered Democrat since I turned 18 and have always voted exclusively for Democrat candidates, and I do not expect that to change, purely because the Republicans are so much worse than the Democrats and all Independent/3rd party candidates are totally non-viable.

question: when_decided_pid
text: Originally, I was very young, like 19 or 20 when my older boyfriend told me that I should vote democrat. My family almost never voted and never talked about politics. My boyfriend was in a union at the paper mill. The union always endorsed the democratic candidates. We are no longer married and he now supports Trump. I knew so little about politics when I voted in my first presidential election and voted for Ross Perot based on ads. I have since learned to think for myself and research before every election. But I now always vote democrat as the lesser of two evils.
full_text: Originally, I was very young, like 19 or 20 when my older boyfriend told me that I should vote democrat. My family almost never voted and never talked about politics. I knew so little about politics when I voted in my first presidential election and voted for Ross Perot based on ads. I have since learned to think for myself and research before every election. But I now always vote democrat as the lesser of two evils.   The Democrats have always proclaimed to be the party of the working class, and I have always been part of that class. It would be stupid to vote differently. Unfortunately, they are so far out of touch with how the rest of us live that it barely makes any difference. Bernie Sanders gets it and he should’ve been nominated over Hilary. I vote blue because it’s the only viable choice. I want to vote for independent candidates but cannot because it is the same as throwing away my vote because of our stupid two party voting system.

text: I probably started moving closer to the Democrats after "W" declared "Mission Accomplished" and even moreso after the 2008 election based on Mitch McConnell's attitude towards and treatment of President Obama (by declaring he'll sure Obama is a one term president and refusing to hold a confirmation hearing for Merritt Garland for Scallia's seat on SCOTUS). full_text: I probably started moving closer to the Democrats after "W" declared "Mission Accomplished" and even moreso after the 2008 election based on Mitch McConnell's attitude towards and treatment of President Obama (by declaring he'll sure Obama is a one term president and refusing to hold a confirmation hearing for Merritt Garland for Scallia's seat on SCOTUS). But most definitely since the Republicans turned MAGA (the Tea Partiers were bad enough) and collectively lost their minds, spines, and seemingly all of their principles in their zeal to court favor with the Orange Jesus (or is it Orange Pope now?).   My Father changed jobs/got promoted.   My views on many social issues such as abortion care, health care, minimum wage, building back the Middle Class, and non discrimination policies are more aligned with the Democrats. Plus since the era of Trump and MAGA the Republicans have abandoned all their previous positions on things like a fiscal responsibility, foreign policy (especially in regards to Russia and Ukraine), the validity of science and the rule of law in order to acquiesce to the Orange Jesus in the White House. I feel that the Republicans can no longer be taken seriously and they can no longer be trusted to make any decisions regarding our country. They espouse a pro natalist position but are proposing to slash headstart and Medicare funding and they refuse to do anything to lower the cost of child care and college, and do not support paid family leave for new parents. Their proposed $5000 baby bonus is not serious and would maybe cover 4 months of infant day care where I live (especially since the recently increase minimum wage is only $12.41/hr; almost 55% of a person's wages need to go to childcare costs). I have voted for Republicans in the past (including President, Governor, Congress and other local VA races) but unless the Republicans make some drastic changes and escape the cult they are in I would say it is not very likely that I'd ever vote Republican again.

text: Up until 9/11/2001, I was a democrat. And after that difficult period, I started to see a shift in the democratic platform that didn't resonate with my love of this country. My observations even began to lead me to believe that many democrats actually hate the United States. It's my feeling that Republicans demonstrate more love of country and the allowance for anyone to be the best they can be through learning, hard work and creating a sense of individual self worth. Democrats seemingly want to take the financial achievements from those people described above and give to those unwilling to apply themselves to have a better life. Even when a democrat gets elected, most republicans and/or conservatives, though disappointed, can accept the defeat and move on. Not democrats! Many of them demonstrate an absolute, unabiding hatred for anyone that doesn't think like they do, or believe in what they believe. And so many turn to hateful, hurtful and destructive violence. I don't see that kind of behavior with many republicans or conservatives.

question: when_decided_pid
text: In 2016, when Trump became the Republican candidate, our whole family took a look at what the Republican Party had become and how we had been deceived for decades. When no one was paying attention to the outcome of his criminal case any longer.

question: when_think_pid
text: My first election. I turned 18 in 1999 and I was pretty Jesus-y, much to my liberal parents' confusion, but I voted for Bill Bradley in the primary. I went to see him speak on my college campus. In 2000 I might have voted for McCain over Gore, but Bush was a hard no--I thought he was an idiot nepo baby with terrible half-baked policy plans. I didn't agree with some of McCain's policies, either, but I believed he was a man of character. Clinton was such a shameful embarrssment. Gore is a man of character, as well, but he just didn't have the charisma or retail politicking skills. question: when_think_pid
text: I had been closer to and supported the Republican Party since 1972. Before I could even vote. I began shifting my thinking towards there being no reason to support either the Democratic or Republican Party's after during and after the George W. Bush' presidency, so some time after 2001.
full_text: I had been closer to and supported the Republican Party since 1972. Before I could even vote. I began shifting my thinking towards there being no reason to support either the Democratic or Republican Party's after during and after the George W. Bush' presidency, so some time after 2001.   Parents retired here.   Since 2001 both Party's have drifted farther and farther away from listening to or attempting to do "the will of the People". Reagan was the last Republican president to put the People before Party and Clinton the last to do so. Both were good Presidents and I voted for both of them. The Congress of both parties have been abysmally bad since well before either of those Presidents. Since 2000 the Democrat Party has promised greater equity and freedom for the People but seems to have launched into a crusade towards some kind of hybrid authoritarian socialism, communism or just plain lunacy where Government decides what is best for the nation and We the People as a result are less equal and much less free. The Republican Party likes to campaign on lesser, fairer taxation, smaller, less intrusive government, and more individual freedoms. Problem is they don't deliver on any of that. Even when they hold majorities in both the Executive and Legislative branches. Both sides are too full of themselves and their own narrow vision of what is good for the Country. And the Country? It's been run (into the ground) by a bloated, greedy, uncaring, Bureaucracy which has only grown larger since the 50's and whose only real interest seems to be in maintaining it's own power and control. I strongly supported the current President, Donald Trump, not because he is a Republican or a Democrat, he's been both. I support the man, not the Party. I do because he kept the promises he made his first term and he is keeping the promises he made this term. Most if not all of those promises based on what the people that voted for him (a majority of the country this term) voted for him to achieve. President Trump's methods can be absolutely cringeworthy at times but they get results. And it's about results, not the "work" or the "process" or any of the other useless BS that is used to justify or detract from the job he's doing. I've no idea whom I'll vote for in the next elections. I can tell you it won't be a Republican, Democrat or any other Party. I'll vote for the individuals that most represents the vision of Country I believe in and vote against every one of the incumbents that didn't follow through on their promises. You did ask why.

full_text: This has happened in three specific, escalating notches. First, in 2015, before the first time Trump was elected. Second, I significantly increased my dislike of both parties after January 6. Finally, my worst nightmares came true after Trump took office in 2025. when the Republicans became moral invertebrates (or showed their true essence), and the Democrats flailed and failed, misunderstanding working class Americans entirely. And   I was stunned that the Republican party would put a gross, sleazy, misogynist, incompetent, ignorant, uneducated, draft-dodging crook on the ticket. I was more stunned that the stupid democrats didn't stop it from happening! They utterly failed in their message, focusing instead on dumb, fringe, ideological talking points. THEN in the aftermath of January 6, the Republicans became moral invertebrates (or showed their true essence), and the Democrats flailed and failed, misunderstanding working class Americans entirely. And then, in 2024, they once again snatched defeat from the jaws of victory. Bad Palestine policies, bad immigration policies, bad platform, very bad candidate (for whom I voted, trying to save the country from the very mess it's in now). Disgusted with both parties. Finally, in 2025 the whole insanity of the Trump so-called-presidency has become clear and I am absolutely furious at both parties in Congress and think frankly that they should all be thrown out of Congress and lose their citizenship for being such traitors: Trump is a clear and present danger to the nation. For gods sake what is the matter with them! This is Fall Of Rome level weakness! They need to get him OUT of office, act fast to shore up election safety and voting rights, and make sure this NEVER happens again!   I was offered a better paying job than I had.

question: why_moved_to_current_state
text: A variety of reasons, including extreme costs of living and housing in Seattle.
full_text: A variety of reasons, including extreme costs of living and housing in Seattle.   I have carefully considered the candidates and issues since before I was old enough to vote, in the 1980s, in every election. My main deciding issues have been about environmental issues, and humane issues. In high school, we would compare the actual voting records of those in the legislature, to how we ourselves would vote on bills. In the 1980s, this led to me mostly being aligned decidedly more often with Democratic Party candidates. Since the 1980s, there have not been many Republican environmentalist candidates. Since the turn of the century, the Republican Party has become more and more insane and, well, blatantly mendacious and stupid, and in 2025, seems to be attempting a neo-Nazi fascist coup of sorts. That doesn't make me forget that the Democratic Party is still also largely in the pocket of megadonors, but it does rule out any support I might have considered for Republicans at this point.

I realized that the Republicans were all about tax breaks to the richest one percent and stood on the opposite side of the Democratic issues I just listed. I do not understand why people are voting Republican which in my mind is voting against one's own interest.   To pursue a change of career and the beautiful weather. Also my Parents moved here to retire in a warm climate and two other Brothers moved here as well. My oldest Brother had already moved here so had instant job connections.

It took me a while to figured out the party's switched positions. When I did figure it out, I changed party.
